va, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bourgone","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile.","Americanized form of French   Bourgoin  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bourgoin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alphee, Alyre, Andre, Armand, Aurore, Celina, Emile, Gilberte, Jacques, Laurent, Lucienne, Olivier.","French:","variant of <b>Bourgouin</b> (and, in North America, an altered form of this), a habitational name for someone from Burgundy (Old French <i>Bourgogne</i>), a region of eastern France having Dijon as its center. The area was invaded by the <i>Burgundii</i>, an ancient Germanic tribe from whom it takes its name, in about  AD  480. The duchy of Burgundy, created in 877 by Charles II, King of the Western Franks, was extremely powerful in the later Middle Ages, especially under Philip the Bold (1342–1404; duke from 1363). Compare   Bourgoyne   and   Bourguignon  ."]}]},{"name":"Mathilde","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."],"variants":[{"name":"Mechtild","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]},{"name":"Matilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]},{"name":"Mechtilde","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mathilde de Bourgone was born about 1155, in Diocese of Nevers, France. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Guillaume de Nevers V, Comte de Nevers et d'Auxerre."},"et":{"about 1155–":"umbes 1155–Surnud","1150–1168":"1150–1168","1170–1193":"1170–1193","1171–1181":"1171–1181","1155–Female":"1155–Surnud","1168":"1168","1155":"1155","28 OCT 1170":"28. oktoober 1170","1150":"1150","about 1155":"umbes 1155","1171":"1171","1193":"1193","1181":"1181","1170":"1170","Nevers, France":"Diocèse de Nevers, Prantsusmaa","Nevers,58194,Nièvre,Bourgogne-Franche-Comté,FRANCE,":"Nevers, Nièvre, Bourgogne, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"about 1155–":"noin 1155–Kuollut","1150–1168":"1150–1168","1170–1193":"1170–1193","1171–1181":"1171–1181","1155–Female":"1155–Kuollut","1168":"1168","1155":"1155","28 OCT 1170":"28. lokakuuta 1170","1150":"1150","about 1155":"noin 1155","1171":"1171","1193":"1193","1181":"1181","1170":"1170","Nevers, France":"Diocèse de Nevers, Ranska","Nevers,58194,Nièvre,Bourgogne-Franche-Comté,FRANCE,":"Nevers, Nièvre, Bourgogne, Ranska"},"fr":{"about 1155–":"environ 1155–Décédée","1150–1168":"1150–1168","1170–1193":"1170–1193","1171–1181":"1171–1181","1155–Female":"1155–Décédée","1168":"1168","1155":"1155","28 OCT 1170":"28 octobre 1170","1150":"1150","about 1155":"environ 1155","1171":"1171","1193":"1193","1181":"1181","1170":"1170","Nevers, France":"Diocèse de Nevers, France","Nevers,58194,Nièvre,Bourgogn